INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES(227, 1, '2013-05-10 05:58:24', '2013-05-10 05:58:24', 'la herida en el trabajo de la carretilla elevadora que tiene como resultado paraplejía\r\n\r\nImplicados en este caso incidente en que la demandante sufrió una lesión en el trabajo, mientras que estaba en el curso y el alcance de su empleo. En el momento del incidente, el demandante sólo había trabajado para su empleador por 1 ½ semanas. Su trabajo consistía en operar una carretilla elevadora para descargar las cajas de los remolques. Demandante había alrededor de 9 años de experiencia trabajando con carretillas elevadoras de carga y descarga de productos.\r\n\r\nEn el día del incidente, un compañero de trabajo con más experiencia y antigüedad que el Demandante, le pidió a el demandante que le ayudara a descargar una paleta con cual el estaba teníendo problemas .El demandante fue a remolque y sus co-empleado instruido a el demandante a ponerse de pie junto a la carga y utilizar sus manos por encima de su cabeza para estabilizar la carga mientras que su compañero de trabajo trató de levantar la carga con el montacargas. La carga consistía en 24 cajas de bobinas de acero. La carga pesaba 1,600 libras. mientras que su co-empleado trató de levantar la paleta, toda la carga cayó aplastando demandante. Como resultado del incidente, el demandante quedó paralizado.\r\n\r\nDemandante contenio que el remolque había sido cargado impropiamente. El método utilizado violava todas las normas de la industria. El remolque se cargó incorrectamente a partir de cada concebible consideración. La carga estaba cuatro capas de alto. La capa más alta era la capa más pesada. La carga de 1600 libras bobinas nunca debería haber sido colocado en la parte superior de otra carga. Además, la carga de bobinas era más ancha que la carga directamente debajo asiendo la carga inestable. Peor aún, la tercera y la cuarta capas de los productos fueron colocados en una muy estrecha e inestable segunda capa. Fue formado en esencia como un triángulo invertido con la carga más pesada en cima. Además, la tercera capa, directamente debajo de la paleta 1,600 libras de bobinas eran largas filas de estrecho, poco embalado cajas de techo toldos. Los pedasos sueltos de techo no estaban atados en cualquier forma y, por tanto, resbaló sobre, pasando como el remolque se trasladó en el transporte causando las 1600 libras de carga de bobinas de cambiar y avanzar sobre el remolque al azar.\r\n\r\nEl último factor que hizo este accidente catastrófico fue una virtual certeza de la manera en que la compania de el demandado avia envuelto su carga para el transporte. Las 1600 libras de cajas de bobinas se encogen envueltos juntos pero nunca se adjunta a la paleta de madera. Las normas de la industria exige que el envoltorio retráctil de carga deberá adjuntarse a la paleta para prevenir exactamente el tipo de accidente que ocurrió en este caso. La carga debería haber sido envuelto alrededor de la paleta de acero y luego aver sido unidos. La Empresa Demandada se deberia haber encargo de envolver bien y la garantía de su carga antes de que se le dio al demandado para el transporte.\r\n\r\nEl demandante sufrió una fractura de T-12 con la participación neurológicas. Se le diagnosticó incompleta como un T-12 parapléjico. Lamentablemente, el demandante sufrió tal vez el peor de la columna vertebral perjuicio de una persona puede sufrir. Fue paralizada y en silla de ruedas pero sigio a experimentar un dolor severo de extremidades inferiores y no tiene el control de la vejiga o el intestino.\r\n\r\n* Los resultados pueden variar dependiendo de sus hechos particular y circunstancias legales. Dado que cada caso es diferente, las descripciones de los premios y los casos anteriormente no pretenden ser una garantía de éxito.', 'Negligencia - Solución - $6,100,000*', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'negligencia-solucion-6100000', '', '', '2013-05-20 22:57:03', '2013-05-20 22:57:03', '', 0, 'http://azizipersonalinjury.com/dev/espanol/?p=227', 0, 'post', '', 0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES(290, 1, '2013-05-10 05:53:34', '2013-05-10 05:53:34', '\r\ndangerous condition of public road - no median barrier on freeway\r\n\r\nThis case involved a tragic incident wherein the majority of the family members lost their lives as a result of a head on collision due to lack of a median barrier on the highway in question.\r\n\r\nAt the time of the accident, decedent child 11 years of age, and her sister, then 6 years of age as well as their mother and father, were on their way to Mexicali, to celebrate a birthday party. Traveling behind them were their good friends, along with their son. They were traveling eastbound on the 60 Freeway in the number 1 lane at approximately speed of 65 mph. Another driver traveling westbound on the 60 Freeway in the number 1 lane, lost control of her vehicle and for unknown reasons traveled across the dirt median between the east and westbound lanes of the 60 Freeway and hit the decedents vehicle head on. The impact caused fatal injuries. The decedents son was at the scene of the accident on the side of the freeway and watched his family die.\r\n\r\nThis case was against the State of California for not installing a median barrier at the accident location despite an extensive history of cross median accidents.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n* Results may vary depending on your particular facts and legal circumstances. Because every case is different, the descriptions of awards and cases previously handled are not meant to be a guarantee of success.', 'Dangerous Condition of Public Road - Verdict - $6,500,000*', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '225-revision-2', '', '', '2013-05-10 05:53:34', '2013-05-10 05:53:34', '', 225, 'http://azizipersonalinjury.com/dev/espanol/225-revision-2/', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES(291, 1, '2013-05-10 05:49:06', '2013-05-10 05:49:06', '\r\ndangerous electrical sign\r\n\r\nThis action involved a tragic wrongful death incident, wherein Plaintiff’s husband got electrocuted as a result of coming in contact with a defective/improperly installed sign mounted on the outside wall of Defendant’s property, located in Pacoima, California. The subject sign emitted and/or leaked a high voltage of electricity.\r\n\r\nBeing high school sweet hearts, Plaintiff and her husband had enjoyed many years together. The pictures which Plaintiff had of herself and husband best described how close of a relationship was between Plaintiff and her husband. In fact, at the emergency room following the incident, Plaintiff was so devastated about her husband’s untimely death and wanting to him to be back in her life that she requested preservation of her husband’s seaman so that one day she may have his child.\r\n\r\nThe untimely death of Plaintiff’s husband could have been avoided had the Defendants taken measures to safeguard against the dangerous condition which they knew or should have known. The owner of the subject store, as well as owners of the subject property, failed to remedy a known dangerous condition. Defendants who had changed the plastic facing for the subject sign knew or should have know that the subject sign was not grounded and that the ballast was leaking electricity within the subject sign.\r\n\r\nMoreover, Defendants’ repairman who performed repair-modification work on the subject sign by replacing the light bulbs and changing the ballast knew or should have know about the defects.\r\n\r\nImmediately following the incident, investigation into the matter was conducted by Cal OSHA, Department of Water and Power. The investigative accident report revealed that the subject sign was not properly grounded and that there was a failure in the ballast. Further investigation revealed that due to the referenced defects, the subject sign was emitting over 500 Volts.\r\n\r\nThe defect in the subject sign which electrocuted decedent was created and allowed to exist by Defendants.\r\n\r\nBased on information and belief, prior to the subject incident, Defendant owner and or lessor had leased the store which had the subject sign mounted on the outside wall to Defendant, lessee. As part of the lease agreement, the owner allowed Defendant lessee to conduct construction to convert the store for its own use. In conducting construction, Defendant lessee admitted that through it contractors-agents, it performed repairmodification work on the subject sign. In performing repair-modification of the subject sign, the plastic covering for the sign was removed so that the ballast as well as the light bulbs could be changed.\r\n\r\nThe Defendants admitted that the lack of grounding of the sign was noticeable immediately upon removing of the plastic covering to the subject sign. Despite such fact, Defendants’ agents who performed work on the subject sign failed to remedy the lack of grounding and the defective ballast.\r\n\r\nAdditionally, based on information and belief, the subject sign was repaired-modified by unlicenced improperly trained electrical technicians. During the construction, Defendant owner not only failed to make sure that a licensed contractor was hired to perform any of the construction work, but failed to visit the store to make sure that the construction was being performed in compliance with safety regulations and codes. \r\n\r\n\r\n* Results may vary depending on your particular facts and legal circumstances. Because every case is different, the descriptions of awards and cases previously handled are not meant to be a guarantee of success.', 'Product Liability - Settlement - $3,140,000*', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '223-revision-2', '', '', '2013-05-10 05:49:06', '2013-05-10 05:49:06', '', 223, 'http://azizipersonalinjury.com/dev/espanol/223-revision-2/', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
