INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES(292, 1, '2013-05-11 17:52:50', '2013-05-11 17:52:50', 'colisión de cabeza en la autopista- accidente\r\n\r\nEsta acción implicó un incidente trágico en donde el 10 de julio de 2001, el conductor de el carro conduccia un semi-carro en el curso y el alcance de su empleo que entregaba cerveza. El conductor del camión del demandado se distrajo por una abeja que voló en la ventana del carro. Mientras que el intentava matar la abeja con un conductor de camión del demandado de la matriz de la garantía del cheque cruzó sobre el divisor de centro de la ruta 74 del estado y pegó al vehículo en el cual, la demandante era un pasajero. El impacto era de frente en aproximadamente 50 mph. Como resultado del incidente, la demandante sufrió lesiones severas\r\n\r\n. El acusado contendió que la demandante tenía problemas médicos extensos antes del accidente. El acusado contendió que los problemas médicos previos de la demandante fueron evidenciados por el hecho que en aquel momento del accidente la demandante estaba en camino de tener una exploratorio Endoscopia GI. La demandante había sido hospitalizado tres semanas antes del accidente por insuficiencia cardíaca congestiva, seis meses antes del accidente por pulmonía y aproximadamente un año antes del accidente por una cirugía de by-pass cuádruple. La demandante tenia una historia antes del accidente cerebrovascular, se fracturó su cadera y numerosas otras fracturas, numerosas hospitalizaciones por una insuficiencia cardíaca congestiva, diabetes dependiente en insulina, neuropatía de diabetes, asma, enfisema, hypothyroism e hipertensión de obstrucción pulmonar y crónica. La condición médica de la demandante antes de el accidente era tanto que la demandante necesitava un vigilante 4 horas por día y ella había sido 100% permanentemente incapacitada durante los últimos 26 años debido a su diabetes. Aún más la demandante sólo fue hospitalizada durante 3 días después del accidente y entonces la mandaron a su casa. La demandante se quedó en casa por unos adicionales 5 días y entonces fue hospitalizada por el dolor de pecho y la falta de aliento. Los acusados contendieron inicialmente que todas hospitalizaciones después de que los iniciales 3 días no fueron relacionados a el accidente y entonces tomaron la posición que todo cuidado médico después de que junio 2002 no fueron relacionados a el. Los acusados contienden que las condiciones pre-existente y la condición médica relacionados con el accidente fueron tanto que la esperanza de vida de la demandante en toda probabilidad fuera no más de un año.\r\n\r\n* Los resultados pueden variar dependiendo de sus hechos particular y circunstancias legales. Dado que cada caso es diferente, las descripciones de los premios y los casos anteriormente no pretenden ser una garantía de éxito.', 'Heridas personales - Veredicto - $4,532,771*', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'heridas-personales-veredicto-4532771', '', '', '2013-05-20 22:55:55', '2013-05-20 22:55:55', '', 0, 'http://azizipersonalinjury.com/dev/espanol/?p=292', 0, 'post', '', 0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES(288, 1, '2013-05-10 06:26:21', '2013-05-10 06:26:21', '\r\non-the-job forklift injury resulting in paraplegia\r\n\r\nThis case involved in incident wherein the Plaintiff suffered an on the job injury while in the course and scope of his employment. At the time of the incident, Plaintiff had only worked for his employer for 1 ½ weeks. His job was to operate a forklift to unload crates from trailers. Plaintiff had approximately 9 years experience working with forklifts loading and unloading products.\r\n\r\nOn the day of the incident a co-worker with more experience and seniority than Plaintiff, asked Plaintiff to assist him in unloading a pallet that he was having trouble with. Plaintiff went to the trailer and his co-employee instructed Plaintiff to stand next the load and use his hands raised above his head to stabilize the load as Plaintiff’s co-worker attempted to lift the load with the forklift. The load consisted of 24 boxes of steel coils. The load weighed 1600 pounds. As Plaintiff’s co-employee attempted to lift the pallet, the entire load fell crushing Plaintiff. As a result of the incident, Plaintiff was paralyzed.\r\n\r\nPlaintiff contented that the trailer had been improperly loaded. The method used violated all known industry standards. The trailer was loaded improperly from every conceivable consideration. The load was stacked four layers high. The highest layer was the heaviest layer. The load of 1600 pound coils should never have been placed on top of another load. Additionally, the load of coils was wider than the load directly below it making the load unstable. Worse yet, the third and fourth layers of products were placed on an extremely narrow and unstable second layer. It was essentially shaped like a reversed triangle with the heaviest load on the top. Additionally, the third layer, the one directly below the 1600 pound pallet of coils were long rows of narrow, loosely packed boxes of roof awnings. The lose boxes of roof awnings were not fastened together in any manner and, therefore slid about, shifting as the trailer moved in transport causing the 1600 pound load of coils to shift and move about the trailer haphazardly.\r\n\r\nThe last factor that made this catastrophic accident a virtual certainty was the manner in which the Defendant Company wrapped its load for transport. The 1600 pound boxes of coils were shrink wrapped together but never attached to the wood pallet. Industry standards require that the shrink wrap load must be attached to the pallet to prevent exactly the type of accident that occurred in this case. The load should have been shrink wrapped around the wood pallet and then steel banded together. Defendant Company was responsible for properly wrapping and securing its load before it was given to the Defendant for transport.\r\n\r\nPlaintiff suffered a T-12 fracture with neurological involvement. He was diagnosed as being an incomplete T-12 paraplegic. Sadly, Plaintiff suffered perhaps the worse spinal injury a person can suffer. He was paralyzed and wheelchair bound yet continued to experience severe back and lower extremity pain and he has no bowel or bladder control.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n* Results may vary depending on your particular facts and legal circumstances. Because every case is different, the descriptions of awards and cases previously handled are not meant to be a guarantee of success.', 'Negligence - Settlement - $6,100,000*', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '229-revision-3', '', '', '2013-05-10 06:26:21', '2013-05-10 06:26:21', '', 229, 'http://azizipersonalinjury.com/dev/espanol/229-revision-3/', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
